1.1 Architecture
================

The package is composed of several modules, each responsible for a
distinct layer of functionality:

‘gdocs.el’
     Entry point, user commands, and the ‘gdocs-mode’ minor mode (*note
     Minor mode::).
‘gdocs-auth.el’
     OAuth 2.0 flow, token management, and multi-account support (*note
     Authentication::).
‘gdocs-api.el’
     Asynchronous Google Docs and Google Drive API client built on
     ‘plz.el’ (*note API client::).
‘gdocs-convert.el’
     Bidirectional conversion between org-mode and Google Docs JSON via
     an intermediate representation (IR) (*note Format conversion::).
‘gdocs-diff.el’
     Incremental diff engine that computes the minimal set of API
     requests to synchronize changes (*note Diff engine::).
‘gdocs-sync.el’
     Push/pull orchestration, shadow copy management, and conflict
     detection (*note Sync engine::).
‘gdocs-merge.el’
     Side-by-side conflict resolution interface (*note Conflict
     resolution::).

   All API operations are fully asynchronous via ‘plz.el’ so that Emacs
never blocks during network requests.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Dependencies,  Next: Quick start,  Prev: Architecture,  Up: Overview

1.2 Dependencies
================

The package requires Emacs 29.1 or later and depends on the following
external packages:

   • ‘plz’ (0.7+) for asynchronous HTTP requests.
   • ‘dash’ (2.19+) for list manipulation utilities.
   • ‘s’ (1.13+) for string manipulation utilities.
   • ‘org’ (9.6+), which is built into Emacs.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Quick start,  Prev: Dependencies,  Up: Overview

1.3 Quick start
===============

  1. Obtain OAuth credentials from Google Cloud Console (*note Obtaining
     credentials::).

  2. Configure your credentials in Emacs:

          (setq gdocs-accounts
                '(("personal" . ((client-id . "YOUR-CLIENT-ID")
                                 (client-secret . "YOUR-CLIENT-SECRET")))))

  3. Authenticate: ‘M-x gdocs-authenticate’.

  4. Open an existing Google Doc: ‘M-x gdocs-open’.

  5. Or create a new Google Doc from an org file: ‘M-x gdocs-create’.

   Once a buffer is linked, the ‘gdocs-mode’ minor mode activates
automatically.  Changes are pushed to Google Docs on every save (when
‘gdocs-auto-push-on-save’ is non-nil), and you can pull remote changes
at any time with ‘M-x gdocs-pull’.


