13.1 Comments and suggestions (phase 2)
=======================================

This phase adds full collaboration support: comments, suggestions, and
live change awareness.  It will introduce a new module
‘gdocs-comments.el’ and extend the sync and diff engines.

* Menu:

* Comments system::
* Suggesting mode::
* Periodic polling::
* Planned configuration variables (phase 2)::


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Comments system,  Next: Suggesting mode,  Up: Comments and suggestions (phase 2)

13.1.1 Comments system
----------------------

A side buffer (‘gdocs-comments’) for viewing and managing Google Docs
comments.  The buffer will display in a side window (configurable via a
planned ‘gdocs-comments-side’ option, defaulting to the right) and show
each comment with:

   • Author name and avatar (as text initials).
   • Timestamp.
   • The quoted text the comment is anchored to.
   • Comment body.
   • Reply thread (indented).
   • Resolved status.

   Comments will be linked to positions in the org buffer so that
clicking a comment in the side buffer jumps to the corresponding text.

   Planned commands:

   • ‘gdocs-comments’ — open or toggle the comments side buffer.
   • ‘gdocs-comment-add’ — select a region in the org buffer, then type
     a comment.  Creates a comment anchored to that text in the Google
     Doc.
   • ‘gdocs-comment-reply’ — reply to the comment at point in the
     comments buffer.
   • ‘gdocs-comment-resolve’ — resolve the comment at point.
   • ‘gdocs-comment-delete’ — delete the comment at point.

   Comments will be fetched when pulling and when the comments buffer is
opened.  New comments created locally will be pushed immediately (on
comment creation, not on buffer save).


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Suggesting mode,  Next: Periodic polling,  Prev: Comments system,  Up: Comments and suggestions (phase 2)

13.1.2 Suggesting mode
----------------------

A new command ‘gdocs-suggesting-mode’ will toggle between direct editing
and suggesting mode for the current buffer.  When suggesting mode is
active:

   • The modeline will show ‘GDocs:suggesting’.
   • On push, changes are sent as suggestions (using the Google Docs
     API's ‘InsertText’ / ‘DeleteContentRange’ with
     ‘suggestedInsertionIds’ / ‘suggestedDeletionIds’ fields) rather
     than direct edits.

   When pulling, existing suggestions from other collaborators will be
displayed with distinct faces: green underline for suggested insertions,
strikethrough for suggested deletions.  Each suggestion will be
attributed to its author.

   Planned commands for handling suggestions:

   • ‘gdocs-suggestion-accept’ — accept the suggestion at point.
   • ‘gdocs-suggestion-reject’ — reject the suggestion at point.
   • ‘gdocs-suggestion-accept-all’ — accept all suggestions.
   • ‘gdocs-suggestion-reject-all’ — reject all suggestions.


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Periodic polling,  Next: Planned configuration variables (phase 2),  Prev: Suggesting mode,  Up: Comments and suggestions (phase 2)

13.1.3 Periodic polling
-----------------------

When ‘gdocs-mode’ is active, a timer will poll the Google Doc for
changes at a configurable interval (planned option:
‘gdocs-poll-interval’, default 30 seconds).  Polling checks only the
document revision ID (a lightweight API call).

   Behavior when remote changes are detected:

   • If the local buffer has no unsaved changes: auto-pull and update
     silently, showing a brief message: "Pulled remote changes."
   • If the local buffer has unsaved changes: show a warning in the
     modeline (‘GDocs:conflict’) and notify: "Remote changes detected.
     Save to push your changes, or run ‘gdocs-pull’ to pull."

   Polling will be paused while the buffer is in conflict resolution
mode.  A command ‘gdocs-poll-toggle’ will enable or disable polling per
buffer.


