13.2.1 Google Drive browser
---------------------------

A new module ‘gdocs-drive.el’ will provide a dired-like buffer for
browsing Google Drive.  The command ‘gdocs-drive’ will open the browser,
prompting for an account if multiple are configured.

   The buffer will list files and folders with columns for icon/type
indicator, file name, owner, last modified, and sharing status.  Files
are fetched asynchronously with a loading indicator.

   Planned keybindings:

Key     Action
----------------------------------------------------------------
‘RET’   Open file (Google Doc → org buffer) or enter folder
‘^’     Go up one directory
‘g’     Refresh the listing
‘s’     Search Drive (full-text)
‘m’     Mark a file
‘u’     Unmark a file
‘U’     Unmark all
‘o’     Open file in browser
‘i’     Show file info (metadata, permissions, revisions)
‘d’     Mark for deletion
‘x’     Execute deletions
‘C’     Create a new Google Doc
‘R’     Rename a file
‘T’     Toggle between Google Docs only and all file types
‘S’     Toggle to show only files shared with you
‘q’     Quit the Drive browser

   By default, the browser will show only Google Docs (filtered by MIME
type ‘application/vnd.google-apps.document’).


File: gdocs.info,  Node: Org export backend,  Next: Planned configuration variables (phase 3),  Prev: Google Drive browser,  Up: Drive browser and export (phase 3)

13.2.2 Org export backend
-------------------------

A new module ‘gdocs-export.el’ will register as an org export backend so
that users can use the standard org export dispatcher.  The export menu
key will be ‘g’, so the sequences are:

   • ‘C-c C-e g d’ — export to Google Docs (create new or update
     existing linked Doc).
   • ‘C-c C-e g o’ — export and open in browser.

   The backend will parse the buffer with ‘org-element’, convert to
Google Docs API requests, and create or update the document.  For
buffers already linked to a Google Doc, this is equivalent to
‘gdocs-push’.  For unlinked buffers, it creates a new Google Doc and
links the buffer.


